AB  - Under the big data era, we have witnessed more and more collective actions globally. Interactions between online medias and Internet users largely shape the evolutionary dynamics in online collective actions. Online Medias may post breaking news or funny things to attract individuals or participants. Meanwhile, Internet users and individuals post, share, and discuss funny materials or breaking news, which encourages online medias to broadcast them further. To better investigate the interactions and how online collective action are launched and organized, we classify online Medias into traditional Medias (T) and mobile (social) Medias (M). The Weibo users (W) are taken as the typical type of Internet users (U). Big data of 136 cases are obtained, and for each, we record the dynamic trends of T, M, U & W, and six correlations (R-TM, R-TW, R-TU, R-MW, R-MU, and R-UW) are calculated. It indicates that they are not normally distributed, but their nonlinear transformations seem to follow the normal distributions. The life cycle trends of correlations are obvious: for Prepare stage, the correlation is equal to zero; for the Outbreak stage, the correlation starts at a much higher level, which is about 0.4; for Peak stage, the peak is about 0.8. The peak refers to the situation that the strength of media's manipulating public opinions or individuals' forcing medias to pay attention is the highest; for Vanish stage, the correlation is equaled to zero again. The findings can be used to predict or even manipulate the process of online collective actions.
